Introduction

In this assignment, you will apply various machine learning techniques to predict customer churn using the Telco Customer Churn dataset. The focus will be on using logistic regression, K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN), and discriminant analysis to build predictive models, assess their performance, and interpret the results. You will also explore resampling techniques such as cross-validation and bootstrapping to evaluate model accuracy and uncertainty.

Learning Outcomes

By the end of this assignment, you will be able to:

  • Apply logistic regression and KNN to predict customer churn in a real-world dataset.
  • Use cross-validation to tune hyperparameters and select the optimal model.
  • Interpret model coefficients and explain the influence of predictors on churn likelihood.
  • Implement bootstrapping to estimate uncertainty in model performance metrics.
  • Compare different classification models based on evaluation metrics such as accuracy, recall, and precision.
  • Understand the impact of data preprocessing and feature selection on model outcomes.

Telco Churn Dataset

The Telco Customer Churn dataset from Kaggle contains customer data from a telecom company, with various features describing the customers’ demographics, service usage, and account information. In this assignment we will analyse this data and attempt to predict customer1 in the telecommunications industry.

Relevant material: Lectures 6, 7, 8, and 9; Labs 3 and 4

Exercise 8 (Interpret coefficients) (2 points) Interpret the model coefficients for the model fitted in Exercise 7 and discuss how each predictor affects the likelihood of churn.

Intercept

  • The intercept, \(\hat \beta_0\), -1.5219831 represents the log-odds of churn when all predictors (tenure, MonthlyCharges, and TotalCharges) are equal to zero. In practical terms, it’s less meaningful on its own since having all these predictors equal to zero may not be realistic for this dataset.

Tenure:

  • The coefficient for tenure is \(\hat \beta_1\) = -0.0697637, which is negative. This means that as the number of months a customer has been with the company (tenure) increases, the log-odds of churn decrease.

  • In other words, longer-tenured customers are less likely to churn. For each additional month of tenure, the log-odds of churn decrease by approximately 0.0697637

  • Since the p-value for tenure is less than 0.001 (highly significant), we can confidently say that tenure has a strong negative relationship with churn.

MonthlyCharges

  • The coefficient for MonthlyCharges is 0.0288965, which is positive. This means that as the monthly charges increase, the log-odds of churn increase.

  • In simpler terms, customers who pay higher monthly charges are more likely to churn. For each additional dollar in monthly charges, the log-odds of churn increase by approximately 0.0288965.

  • The p-value for MonthlyCharges is less than 0.001, indicating a statistically significant positive relationship with churn.

TotalCharges

  • The coefficient for TotalCharges is 0.0001846721, which is also positive, but very close to 0. The associated p-value for TotalCharges is 0.0706, which is greater than the conventional significance level of 0.05. This suggests that the relationship between TotalCharges and churn is not statistically significant, meaning it may not be a reliable predictor of churn in this model.

Exercise 10 (K-Nearest Neighbors Classification) (2 points) Train a KNN classifier using a set of predictors that you select; you may use the same predictors as in Exercise 9 or something other subset entirely. Use 10-fold cross-validation to find the optimal value of \(k\). Set your seed to your student number for reproducibility. You need not test every possible value of k; instead, you can use a grid of 10ish different values. Tip: experiment with different subsets of features and compare the cross-validation accuracy.

Marking guide

  • 1 point for set up (folds and grids for \(k\))

  • 1 point for selecting the best value of \(k\) (the one that obtains the highest accuracy)

# Set up cross-validation
set.seed(2024311)
train_control <- trainControl(method = "cv", number = 10) # 10-fold cross-validation

# Train the KNN model with cross-validation to find the optimal k
knn_model1 <- train(Churn ~ tenure + MonthlyCharges + SeniorCitizen + Contract,
                    data = train_set,
                    method = "knn",
                    trControl = train_control,
                    tuneLength = 10) # Automatically test 10 values of k

# View the results for the first KNN model
plot(knn_model1)
# Extract the best k value from the trained model
optimal_k <- knn_model1$bestTune$k

In my case, the optimal number of neighbors as determined by 10-fold CV is: 19.

Aside:

optimal at endpoints

If the optimal \(k\) is at one of the endpoints, expand your grid to check for smaller or larger values that might perform better.

Exercise 11 (Retrain KNN) (2 points) Retrain the KNN model using the optimal value of \(k\) as determined by Exercise 10. Use your student number as a seed for reproducibility.

# Retrain the KNN model with the optimal k
set.seed(2024311) # Setting seed for reproducibility

optimal_k <- knn_model1$bestTune$k

# Train the KNN model using the optimal k
knn_model_final <- train(Churn ~ tenure + MonthlyCharges + SeniorCitizen + Contract,
                         data = train_set,
                         method = "knn",
                         trControl = train_control,
                         tuneGrid = data.frame(k = optimal_k))

# View the final model summary
print(knn_model_final)

Exercise 12 (Seeds for KNN) (1 point) Explain why setting a seed might be important when using the KNN algorithm. In other words, describe the non-deterministic component of this algorithm.

KNN can experience ties in the majority vote, so the end result will be different from run to run (ties are split by random assignment).

Exercise 15 (Confusion Matrices) (3 points) Use the fitted model from Exercise 7, Exercise 9, Exercise 10, Exercise 11, Exercise 13 and Exercise 14 to predict if the customers in our test set will churn. Report the confusion matrix for each model.

# Load required libraries
library(caret)
library(MASS)
library(knitr)

# Function to display confusion matrix using kable
display_conf_matrix <- function(conf_matrix, model_name) {
  kable(as.table(conf_matrix), caption = paste("Confusion Matrix for", model_name))
}

# Logistic Regression Model Prediction
log_reg_pred <- predict(log_reg, newdata = test_set, type = "response")
log_reg_pred_class <- ifelse(log_reg_pred > 0.5, "Yes", "No")
log_reg_conf_matrix <- confusionMatrix(as.factor(log_reg_pred_class), test_set$Churn)
display_conf_matrix(log_reg_conf_matrix, "Logistic Regression Model")

Exercise 17 (Bootstrapping for uncertainty) (3 points) Use bootstrapping to estimate the uncertainty in the winning model’s predictions from Exercise 16. That is calculate the standard deviation for recall. (1 bonus point) Construct a 95% confidence interval for recall.

# Load required libraries
library(boot)


# Define a function to calculate recall for bootstrapping
bootstrap_recall <- function(data, indices) {
  # Resample the data
  boot_data <- data[indices, ]
  
  # Fit the logistic regression model
  log_reg_boot <- glm(Churn ~ tenure + MonthlyCharges + TotalCharges, 
                      data = boot_data, 
                      family = binomial)
  
  # Predict on the original test set
  predictions <- predict(log_reg_boot, newdata = test_set, type = "response")
  predicted_class <- ifelse(predictions > 0.5, "Yes", "No")
  
  # Calculate the confusion matrix
  conf_matrix <- confusionMatrix(as.factor(predicted_class), test_set$Churn)
  
  # Extract the recall (sensitivity)
  recall <- conf_matrix$byClass["Sensitivity"]
  
  return(recall)
}

# Set seed for reproducibility
set.seed(2024)

# Perform bootstrapping with 1000 iterations
boot_recall_results <- boot(data = train_set, 
                            statistic = bootstrap_recall, 
                            R = 1000)

# Calculate the standard deviation of the bootstrapped recall
mean_recall <- mean(boot_recall_results$t)
std_dev_recall <- sd(boot_recall_results$t)

# Calculate 95% confidence intervals
conf_intervals_recall <- quantile(boot_recall_results$t, probs = c(0.025, 0.975))
